The OCaml version (for 2 lists) is almost as good as clojure<p><pre><code>    List.map2 ( + ) a b;;
</code></pre>
However, for 3 or more lists, Clojure definitely wins (since there&#x27;s no variadic equivalent of map in OCaml) -<p><pre><code>    let x = List.map2 ( + ) a b in List.map2 ( + ) x c;;
</code></pre>
Which got me wondering, is there a particular reason why only a `map2` exists in OCaml?
